>I was under the impression that you had a hand in StormC -
>are you planning on AltiVec support? Even if it's inefficient.

I don't work on the compiler. Additing AltiVec support to
compilers is VERY difficult. The AltiVec instructions do *not*
work on the normal PowerPC registers, they work with their own.
This means you can't simply compile a function and intermediately
attempt to use an AltiVec instruction instead of a series of
other instructions. The switching between the register types
(through memory/cache, because there is no other way to do it)
would defeat any advantage. And I didn't talk about parallelism
yet. How should a compiler detect a function, which is
parallelizable? The common algorithm suitable for AltiVec is
a loop which does some operation with an operand, and in
every loop the next operand is processed. Be happy to write
the compiler algorithm to find such loops suitable for
AltiVec compilation. The actual operation must be *the same*
for all operangs, because otherwise you can't keep several
operands in one AltiVec register, because the operands might
go other paths. One single comparison or branch inside such
an algorithm might force the compiler to give up the idea
of using AltiVec instructions, because the operands don't go
the same way all the time.

I still say, that the only suitable way of supporting AltiVec
is using ASM and reorganize the algorithms to make them
suitable for AltiVec code.

