@node 07924.001
Subject: Re: Altivec
From: Sam Jordan <sam_jordan@spin.ch>
Date: Sun, 12 Sep 1999 17:58:42 +0200

Am 12-Sep-99 schrieb Alan Buxey:

>hi,

>>The processor is the same, but a processor doesn't make
>>a whole computer. Calculating several millions of digits
>>of PI is certainly funny, but actually most of today's
>>most wanted applications are graphics/multimedia-based.
>>And the fastest processor doesn't help, if the other
>>components aren't working at a similar high level. And
>>also don't forget, that the AMIGA-OS *will remain* 68K,
>>and that mode-switches won't have zero-cost, too (always
>>talking about AMIGA-OS direct mode, for other OS the
>>situation is different).

>the 68k will be under emulation....theres no switches any more.

WRONG!

The switches are still there. You should understand that the
software architecture won't change with these new boards. We will
still have two CPU's interacting with eachother. One is real and
the other one is virtual.

Mode switches are task switches between the emulator task and
the native running task. And we know that task switches aren't
neglectable, they can be compared to thread switches on Unix
systems. And assume someone is calling lots of AMIGA-OS functions
then the sum makes a difference. Sure, the switches will get
faster, but they still will have some overhead. Even more as
the pagetable is switched, too, because the emulator has its
own.

>>Therefore please please don't try to compare the Amiga-G4
>>architecture with other G4-based architectures.

>when the G4 is being used, it'll be used...no more cache flushes etc in
>the background. its just the gfx that we'll have to wait for

The difference between native and emulation/interpreter is usually
around a factor 20-50. Which means, that an application which spends
a few percent in 68K code (i.e. OS) will run twice as slow as if it
was running completely PPC. And finally you should not forget, that
the emulator often is woken up due to 68k interrupt processing. The
G4 won't run at 100% efficiency even for plain PPC applications.

It is still useless to try to pretend that the G4 based AMIGA's will
have the same efficieny than other G4-based architectures. It surely
will speed up things a lot, but this discussion is simply about the
comparison between the AMIGA and the other architectures.

